<Review>I am disabled with 15 years prior mechanical/automotive repair experience. I have a full size Ford Econoline handicap equipped van with full hand controls needing a front end alignment after front end damage due to an accident. I spoke with Steve often during the front end steering repair on my van. Steve has great customer service skills and was always quick to provide status and updates involving on each step of service from beginning to end. Manager Louis was very professional and understanding to my concerns as a disabled individual. Louis seemed highly competent and very knowledgeable and was eager to work with me on labor and parts costs. I had been in an accident which caused right front end damage requiring replacement of many parts. Louis took the time to clearly explain and show me what the damaged parts looked like and was very helpful and willing to track down replacement parts and work hard to make sure things worked properly. Gosh Ford Quick Lane did a fantastic front end repair and alignment considering the amount of damage and time required to repair my van. I highly recommend Gosh Ford Quick Lane to anyone seeking trustworthy automotive repair at very reasonable prices.<//Review>< Rating>

< Review>
If it were not for what appears to be excellent body work by Gosch Collision on my vehicle, I would be giving them 1 star. The reason - incredibly poor customer communication / service.

Gosch Collision set a strong expectation of superior customer communication by e-mailing me almost daily reports on the status of my repair until four (4) days before the repair would be completed and the vehicle would be ready for pick up.

When we came to pick up our vehicle, we were informed by the service rep that there was a problem related to paperwork from our insurance company. The rep said he heard about the issue five (note this: FIVE) days before but did not do what was needed to resolve the issue and waited until we arrived to pick up the vehicle. We could have been working on getting the required paperwork from the insurance company FIVE days earlier but the Gosch rep decided not to communicate with us until we came to get the vehicle. The rep said he heard about the issue on Thursday but because he was off on Friday, and he doesn't work on the weekends, and he must have had other things on his mind on Monday, we did not hear about the insurance issue until we came to the Gosch office at 2:00PM. He he made a simply phone call on Thursday, we could have had it all resolved well in advance of the Monday pickup time. I saw a number of other office people at there so even if he were not available to call me, someone esle certainly could have done that.

Of course, even with the rep away on Friday, that did not stop their system from sending us the following note that day that said:

Hi Patrick,

We are nearing completion. If we encounter any delays, we'll call you.

Gosch Collision

So, where was the call their system promised?

My point is - if you decide to set yourself up as practitioners of superior customer communications, then you darn well better deliver.

I did not expect superior communication from a collision company but Gosch created that expectation with their e-mailed communications. Too bad at least one employee was incapable, or unwilling, to deliver on that promise.

We did finally get our vehicle back several hours after showing up at the Gosch Collision office in Hemet and, as I noted earlier, the body work appears to be well done but the poor customer service and lack of critical communication was completely unacceptable.

FOLLOWUP: NOVEMBER 12, 2019

As if to confirm my feelings on poorly handled communication, please see their NOVEMBER 11, 2019 response to my initial comments from 9 MONTHS AGO. Nine months to post an apology. REALLY?? Honestly, as far as I am concerned, you would have been better off not commenting back at all.<//Review>

< text>
I have been holding off on this review to see if my situation would be rectified, but after several attempts it has not been addressed.
I had some damage to my SS Camaro repaired here; hood and fender painted and front bumper replaced.  The responsible party was paying for the damage which I was initially told would be fine for them to call in the payment once the work was complete, only to find out late on Friday afternoon that the payment had to come from me.  This caused a delay and extra expenses for a rental over the weekend.
I get the car back and the paint looked great but driving home my car started to run badly and my check engine light came on.  After an initial inspection, I found the MAF sensor unplugged.  Okay, no big deal, I plugged it in and problem solved.  After about a month, I finally noticed that the Camaro emblem was not replaced on the fender that was painted.  I called Gosch Collision and left a message for Carlos asking if he had any letters laying around there and asked him to call me back to resolve the issue.  I work out of town and it is very difficult for me to get there during business hours.
Finally I took a day off and went in there in person to talk to Carlos.  He stated that he never received my voicemail.  I showed him the missing emblem and asked why I did not receive any touch up paint as the paint on the bumper and fender was very thin and I had some rock chips to cover up.  Carlos stated that he would talk to his manager about the emblem and get me some touch up paint and call me once he confirmed.
No call, nothing.
I bought my car from Gosch Auto Group so naturally I wanted to get it repaired here because it was close to my house.  Lesson learned.< /text>

<rating>2</rating>< Text>
Past times I've ordered here, the staff were all very friendly and nice. And it's amazing pizza, really good option for parties. However, this time picking up my order, I was seen coming in, stood at the front register for 5 minutes without being helped, only 1 family was there already eating. So I looked behind the higher counter to get someone's attention, I was ignored as 2 employees were in the middle of a casual conversation... I waited til a pause and asked for my order.

Normally this'd be fine by me, no big deal. But when I let the cashier know I'd been waiting there 5 minutes, her 1st instinct was to argue: "Okay well you need to be here at the register." "I was." "Oh, sorry".

I'd have taken my $6 tip to her back if I could. It's not the customer's job to be seen, it is the employees job to see the customer and serve them. I am paying you.</Text>

<user_id>106713914240470940178<//user_id>< user_name>
Robert Castillo< /user_name>
<time>1498622694154</time><Rate>3< /Rate>< text>
I take time to reflect on my experiences over time in order to prevent writing in frustration or without considering the perspective of employees of the service industry.

The TL;DR version goes like this: Over the last month or 2 I've ordered the same pizza 5 times. They have gotten the order wrong 4 times, but when confronted they try to make it right. 3 stars is fair because the food is good and the staff is cooperative when they error. But I don't understand what's so difficult about putting the correct toppings on a pizza when the toppings appear on the receipt and presumably get communicated to the staff.

Full Version (if anyone is interested):

I order a specialty pizza - The Italian Garlic Supreme - and I tend to get it delivered because I'm originally from a small town that didn't have any restaurants with delivery services, so having food brought to my door is still a novelty.

The pizza usually arrives without the green onions, a topping that is included standard with this pizza. The first time this happened I let it go. I figured, "meh, probably training someone, whatever". The second time I order it - a week later - Same issue. I called them up to let them know this happened twice now and they offered me a discount on the pie. Cool. Third time...same issue except while ordering I ask if they have the green onions and get verbal confirmation that they'll make it on the pie. When the pizza arrived without them I called again and they offered to send the driver back out with the onions in a plastic cup. I thought that was kind, but it was already 9pm, I hadn't eaten since breakfast, I had to work the next day, and I didn't want to wait up and let my pizza get cold, so I declined and was offered a free pizza next time I ordered. I accepted.

Fast forward: I try to redeem my free pizza and its a different manager who is suspicious and doesn't understand why that would happen, and treats me like I'm trying to pull something because the previous manager didn't leave a note like she said she would, but they give me the free pizza and it's perfect! Yum!

Most recently: I think I have it figured out. I ask for EXTRA Green Onions. That's right! if they don't put their standard topping on their own pizza I'll draw their attention to it! Didn't work. Pizza arrived tonight without green onions. I'm starting to feel like they're screwing with me. I call back and admittedly was a bit rude - They asked me if I could hold and I was like "No!" - and was offered a free pizza next time, but after my last experienced I declined and they gave me this one free.

I'm not trying to be unreasonable, but I know what I want. And according to their MENU I should be able to have it. Further, when you're spending $30 on a pizza you want to get what you want.

Overall, the food is good and the people are friendly, but getting what you order is not easy. And if you can, pick up is better. When you order delivery they say 45 minutes to an hour, but in my experience its usually a little over an hour and the pizza is sometimes luke-warm.</text>

There are many things that make an experience amazing. First of all was the great service from Ariel, she was super tentative and had great suggestions. <user_name>Jana Gill</user_name><Rate>5</Rate>< Review>
I have a bunch of food intolerances which make it hard to eat out. My husband and I stayed at the Ritz for our anniversary and went to the restaurant to see if they could accommodate me. From the hostess to the waiter to the chef they were so helpful and didn't make me feel bad at all. The chef made me a meal specific to my allergies and it was delicious. We were both very happy with our food, the service, and atmosphere in general (live music) and would definitely go back.</Review>

<rating>5</rating>< Review>
We are locals and try to go either Fri or Sat night when they have live music. But that aside, the food is AMAZING. We have taken loads of people there and no one has been disappointed ever. The burger is off the charts. The scallops are fantastic. And believe it or not, they have a gluten free pita bread that is so delicious, many people prefer it to regular bread. They are extremely accommodating for substitutions as well (like for example, having half sweet potato and half regular fries). Love that they use organic/locally sources when possible. That's what brought us there to start, but the quality of the food and the ambience kept us there.<//Review>

None< /resp>
< Text>
Meh.

Any park that is mainly concrete or pavement is not a park; it's a re-purposed parking lot.

Though the developers who helped create this park claim it is mainly for children, it is not child friendly. There's a small corner of the park with "toddler playground" equipment, but it is not grassed in, the creator or designer chose to use a cushy foam instead. The play equipment is actually pretty good, too bad the designers decided to make the rest of the park look like an outdoor conference room.

Though the intent was to have an area adults and children could play in and around, dogs outnumber children 20:1. The grassy knoll adjacent to the playground is fenced off indefinitely. It looks nice, but it fails in its original intent, fails in its most useful purpose (a dog park) and fails as any sort of park. There aren't even any decent shade trees and it is certainly not restful.

If taxpayer dollars helped create this area the public was bilked.</Text>

{'time': 1618942028378, 'text': 'Hi Brandon, sorry you didn\'t have a good experience at Paso market Walk. We worked very hard to build, lease, beautify and proudly provide jobs for the hard working people who make it happen on our campus. All of the merchants are "mom and pop" shops if you will, and fulfilling dreams they envision. Products are freshly made, handpicked and less a plastic product bag. Blood, sweat and tears went into every aspect of this property - and in this day and age we live on reviews and "stars."  We encourage shop local and support small business. The prices may be "higher" than fast food or middle of the grocery store, but you\'re supporting the small guy and that is who we strive to support. We are not looking to trap anyone, and appreciate the tourism our community envelopes. They bring a lot of revenue to our wonderful city...but thank you for your feedback! Have a great day.'}</Resp>

<user_name>Aaron Smathers< /user_name><user_id>105808432062812751651<//user_id>< Review>
I have been going to BigBrand for several years now. They attracted me as a customer with free flat repairs, free tire rotations, and low price guarantee.

The problem with free rotations and flat repairs is the wait, always 1 hour minimum for a 5 minute job. Obviously they want to sell you new tires every time you come in for a free service. I bought 4 kumos (70k mile warranty) for my Acura at their shop and after 30k miles I went in for another rotation and they wouldn't rotate and said I need new tires. I wasn't offered any warranty assistance.

Last month I needed tires for my Mazda and asked them to price match tire buyer dot com on a set of Firestone Firehawk Indy 500. They couldn't beat the price and would only get within  about $40 of it. I wasn't offered a free set of tires like they advertise as you can see in my attached photo.

Today I went in for an oil change I had an appointment at 9AM. My first red flag went up when he asked if I was going to wait for it, of course it's an oil change takes me 20 minutes to do myself.  I asked if it was going to be a while and was told it would be done within the hour. Well at 936AM my car finally moves into the shop. Next red flag goes up when I watch the lube tech look under the hood for a few minutes with confusion.  I go out there and ask him if he is looking for tor filter location and he said yes. I told him it is under the car near the drain plug.  At 1015AM I am told by the salesperson that they cannot get the old oil filter off.  I asked if they can have a more experienced person try, so he said he would get "The Mechanic" to try. They have 10 people working on cars out there but only one is a mechanic? The mechanic gets the filter off in under 30 seconds and returns to his work.  They spend 30 more minutes refilling the oil, replacing filter,  and resetting the oil monitor. At 1045AM the job is done. Almost 2 hours for an oil change AND I had an appointment!

I would recommend you only take your vehicle here if you can drop it off for a day or two and not care how long it takes them.  There are a few other places in town that offer the same free rotations, flat repairs, and low price guarantees. I might be going to a different store from now on.<//Review>

< userid>
102997608866593249159<//userid>
<user_name>Cameron California</user_name><Time>1495226152745<//Time><Rate>2</Rate>< review>
I don't usually write reviews, but my experience at the Santa Maria Big Brand Tire was negative enough that I feel it's worth sharing. I went in today for a set of new tires. After signing the paperwork I was told that they were a little behind schedule so it would be about 1.5 hours before I would get my car back. When scheduling the appointment I had seen a web page describing a "50/50 challenge" (tire change in 50 minutes or you get $50 off). So, naturally, I mentioned that I'd seen that online and I was wondering if that applied. The attendant at the desk asked me to wait for a moment while he went into the shop and, when he returned, told me they would do what they could to finish the job in under 50 minutes.

Fast forward 32 minutes later... I hear my name and walk up to the counter. They finished 18 minutes early! I was impressed, to say the least.  However, that's when my mood changed. When I got to the counter a worker from the shop (who I assumed was the manager, but didn't confirm) poked his head in to ask if they beat the 50/50 challenge. When it's confirmed that they did he made a point of loudly saying (i'm paraphrasing) "Of course, because we pushed back everyone else" so that everyone in the waiting room could hear, making me look like a jerk. I was then informed by the attendant that the 50/50 usually needs to be requested when the online appointment is made, that way they can plan accordingly.

As a customer, it isn't my job to know the ins and outs of Big Brand Tire's policies. I'm an easy going guy. If they had told me when I arrived that I needed to mention the 50/50 challenge when I booked the appointment, oh well, I would've been sure to do it the next time. Unfortunately for them, there wont be a next time. The way the manager(?) rudely announced to everyone that I was making them late was unprofessional and immature. I had just spent over $500 at their business and I was immediately put down because THEY had not informed me about THEIR business policies when I had first arrived.

Normally I would give them 1 star, but I'm giving them 2 because they did finish the job early and the attendant I spent most of the time speaking to was calm, collected, and courteous (unlike the other guy!). I'll let them have the second star for that because they won't be getting my business again.

**Note to anyone that still decides to go here: Make sure you call them when making an appointment and mention the 50/50 challenge! That way you won't get stuck with a long wait time like some of the other commenters (or at least you'll get $50 off your purchase!)**<//review>

< Review>
Having to update this review to 2 stars. Been trying to reach customer service to schedule a 2nd appt to pick up last two remaining items. One is a fairly new AC unit, definitely wanted it stored. CANNOT REACH ANYBODY BUT MUSIC, and now I am being forced to junk the item. Movers great, customer service sucks. Two stars it is.

First time to use a storage company. Rates pretty reasonable, and for the actual move, these guys were great. Quick, careful with the items, and helpful when I had questions. I had a glass table which couldn't be moved as is, since glass was stuck to the base. They recommended they're disassembling it, forthright with me about signing a waver. The table was super old anyway, so ultimately decided to junk the item. I was just glad they recommended options that were feasible. I also need to schedule another appointment to pick up two more items, one was a portable AC unit that I couldn't part with just yet in this hot weather.
